    <section class="container section-pad pillar">
      <h2>Complete Guide to Electrical Panel Upgrades in West Michigan</h2>
      <p>
        An electrical panel — sometimes called a breaker box, service panel, or load center — is the central hub of every
        electrical system in a building. It takes utility power from your meter and distributes it through individual
        breakers to every circuit in your home. When the panel is undersized, aging, or made by a brand with documented
        defects, every load downstream of it carries the same risk: nuisance trips, voltage instability, or in the worst
        case, a panel fire.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide covers what a panel upgrade actually is, how to tell when you need one, what's involved in the work, and
        the West Michigan specifics — permitting, utility coordination, and the panel brands we see most often in Holland,
        Grand Rapids, Hudsonville, and the surrounding lakeshore communities.
      </p>

      <h3>What "Panel Upgrade" Actually Means</h3>
      <p>
        "Panel upgrade" is shorthand for any of three distinct scopes that often overlap:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Panel replacement</strong> — removing the existing breaker enclosure and installing a new one of the
          same amperage (typically 100 → 100 or 200 → 200). Done when the panel itself is failing but service capacity is
          adequate.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Service upgrade</strong> — increasing total service amperage (typically 100 → 200, or 200 → 400). Includes
          new service entrance conductors, meter base, and main breaker. Requires utility coordination.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Code-driven upgrade</strong> — replacing a panel because the brand has documented defects (Zinsco,
          Federal Pacific Stab-Lok) regardless of size or condition. Insurance carriers increasingly require these.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Most homes that "need a panel upgrade" actually need a combination: 100 → 200 amp service upgrade plus a modern
        panel that has spare breaker slots and supports the AFCI/GFCI protections required by current code.
      </p>

      <h3>How to Know You Need One</h3>
      <p>
        The most common signs we see during walkthroughs across West Michigan:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Breakers trip during normal use</strong> — when the AC starts, when the dryer runs with the dishwasher,
          or randomly without explanation. <a href="/blog/why-breakers-trip">Why breakers trip</a> covers the causes in
          detail.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Lights flicker under load</strong> — brief dimming when motors start is normal in 100-amp service homes,
          but persistent or whole-house flickering signals an undersized service. See
          <a href="/blog/flickering-lights-when-to-worry">flickering lights: when to worry</a> for the triage guide.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>No spare breaker slots</strong> — you can't add a circuit without removing one, or the panel is already
          packed with tandem (double-wide) breakers.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>You're planning an EV charger</strong> — Level 2 chargers add 40–48 amps of load. On a 100-amp panel
          already running central AC, that's usually too much. See
          <a href="/blog/do-i-need-a-panel-upgrade-for-an-ev-charger">do I need a panel upgrade for an EV charger?</a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>You see Federal Pacific or Zinsco on the cover</strong> — replace regardless of condition. See
          <a href="/blog/zinsco-fpe-panel-replacement">why Zinsco and Federal Pacific panels need to go</a>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Burning smell from the panel or outlets</strong> — turn off the main breaker and call. See
          <a href="/blog/burning-smell-from-outlet">burning smell from an outlet: what to do in the next 5 minutes</a>.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Sizing: 100 vs 200 vs 400 Amp</h3>
      <p>
        Service amperage is the maximum current the panel can pass through the main breaker. 200 amp is the modern
        residential default — large enough to support central AC, electric range, EV charger, and future loads without
        running near capacity. 100 amp service was standard from the 1950s through the 1990s and is still adequate for
        smaller homes with gas-heavy appliances and no EV.
      </p>
      <p>
        The sizing decision comes down to a documented <a href="/glossary/load-calculation">load calculation</a> per
        NEC Article 220, not a guess based on square footage. We run this on every quote. See
        <a href="/blog/100-amp-vs-200-amp-panel">100 amp vs 200 amp panel: which does your home need?</a> for the
        decision framework, and <a href="/blog/200-amp-vs-400-amp-service">200 amp vs 400 amp service compared</a> for
        larger homes considering 400 amp.
      </p>

      <h3>What Replacement Involves</h3>
      <p>A standard 100 → 200 amp upgrade in West Michigan runs 6–10 hours of on-site work and includes:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Permit pull with the local AHJ.</li>
        <li>Utility coordination — the meter is pulled for the work window (typically 2–4 hours).</li>
        <li>Removing the existing panel and verifying the <a href="/glossary/service-entrance">service entrance</a> conductors are sized for the new amperage.</li>
        <li>Replacing the meter base if corroded or undersized.</li>
        <li>Installing the new panel, typically Square D QO/Homeline, Siemens, or Eaton CH.</li>
        <li>Verifying <a href="/glossary/bonding-vs-grounding">bonding and grounding</a> per NEC Article 250 — including ground rod connections and water-pipe bonds.</li>
        <li>Re-terminating every circuit with proper labeling.</li>
        <li>Final inspection by the AHJ.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        We coordinate the utility cut, pull the permit, and close out the inspection. You don't deal with paperwork — see
        <a href="/blog/electrical-panel-upgrade-cost">electrical panel upgrade cost: what determines the price</a> for
        the full pricing breakdown.
      </p>

      <h3>Common Pairings: Generator, EV, Code Corrections</h3>
      <p>
        Most panel upgrades we run aren't standalone. Common pairings:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Generator install.</strong> A whole-home generator needs an automatic transfer switch tied directly to
          the panel. Doing both together saves a second mobilization and one permit. See
          <a href="/blog/how-to-size-a-whole-home-generator">how to size a whole-home generator for a Michigan home</a>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>EV charger install.</strong> The 200-amp upgrade and the EV circuit go in during the same window. See
          <a href="/blog/level-1-vs-level-2-ev-charger">Level 1 vs Level 2 EV charger</a> and
          <a href="/blog/where-to-install-ev-charger">where to install your EV charger</a>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Code corrections.</strong> Older homes with the panel open are the time to address knob-and-tube,
          aluminum branch wiring, or missing AFCI/GFCI protection. See
          <a href="/blog/knob-and-tube-wiring-what-to-do">knob-and-tube wiring: what to do if you still have it</a> and
          <a href="/blog/aluminum-wiring-what-to-do">aluminum wiring: what to do if you have it</a>.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>West Michigan Specifics</h3>
      <p>
        Holland, Hudsonville, Zeeland, and Grand Rapids each have slightly different permit processes and inspection
        timing, but the underlying NEC adoption is the same (2020 NEC with Michigan amendments). Consumers Energy and DTE
        each have their own service-coordination process for the meter pull, with typical scheduling 5–10 business days
        out. Holland Board of Public Works runs a faster turnaround in their service territory.
      </p>
      <p>
        Older lakeshore neighborhoods (downtown Holland, Saugatuck, parts of Macatawa) often have undersized service
        drops and corroded meter bases that drive the scope larger than originally quoted. We identify these during the
        walkthrough so the quote reflects the real scope, not a sales-friendly underestimate.
      </p>
